concepts like young woman,

00:47:43.760 --> 00:47:45.520
like Juliet, and sun, and radiance,

00:47:45.520 --> 00:47:48.200
and all that are also in
different brain regions,

00:47:48.200 --> 00:47:49.290
if you've got more connections

00:47:49.290 --> 00:47:50.130
between different brain regions,

00:47:50.130 --> 00:47:54.280
you have more scope for linking
seemingly unrelated ideas,

00:47:54.280 --> 00:47:55.420
which is the basis of metaphor,

00:47:55.420 --> 00:47:57.570
something that George
Lakoff here at Berkeley

00:47:57.570 --> 00:48:00.240
has published on extensively.

00:48:00.240 --> 00:48:05.240
- So from an apparent pathology

00:48:05.470 --> 00:48:08.410
that you prove to be a pathology,

00:48:08.410 --> 00:48:13.410
you come to an understanding
of the causes in the brain,

00:48:13.590 --> 00:48:17.000
and then from that, in addition to saying,

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:20.100
yeah, this is real and
this is what's going on,

00:48:20.100 --> 00:48:22.610
you wind up speculating,

00:48:22.610 --> 00:48:24.564
and it is just speculation,

00:48:24.564 --> 00:48:28.720
that we can get to the big questions.

00:48:28.720 --> 00:48:31.560
- Correct.
- Namely, what is creativity,

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:35.140
is a process like the
one we've identified,

00:48:35.140 --> 00:48:40.120
going on to a greater extent in the brain

00:48:40.120 --> 00:48:43.230
and helping us understand
what creativity is.

00:48:43.230 --> 00:48:45.400
- Exactly, so from the particular

00:48:45.400 --> 00:48:47.823
to the broad, general questions.

00:48:49.620 --> 00:48:50.730
Gives you an experimental foothold

00:48:50.730 --> 00:48:52.960
for understanding things like metaphor,

00:48:52.960 --> 00:48:55.550
which is, being so elusive.

00:48:55.550 --> 00:48:58.380
- So in a way what's
really kind of interesting

00:48:58.380 --> 00:49:01.290
as one has this conversation with you

00:49:01.290 --> 00:49:05.080
is all of these factors that led you

00:49:05.080 --> 00:49:09.253
to become a neurologist
in a study of the brain,

00:49:10.960 --> 00:49:14.360
build pieces of a platform

00:49:14.360 --> 00:49:17.760
from which you can not
only look at pathologies,

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:21.290
but also speculate
about the big questions.

00:49:21.290 --> 00:49:22.511
- Yeah, absolutely, and neurology

00:49:22.511 --> 00:49:23.950
is one of the few professions

00:49:23.950 --> 00:49:26.820
where you can do that,
behavioral neurology

00:49:26.820 --> 00:49:28.590
and cognitive neuroscience,

00:49:28.590 --> 00:49:31.689
where any time you see a
patient with a disorder,

00:49:31.689 --> 00:49:32.980
it's a curious disorder,

00:49:32.980 --> 00:49:34.940
you come face to face with
the fundamental questions

00:49:34.940 --> 00:49:37.366
that philosophers have raised
about the mind and brain

00:49:37.366 --> 00:49:40.330
since, for the last 2,000 years.

00:49:40.330 --> 00:49:43.850
- And you, in the last
chapter of your book,

00:49:43.850 --> 00:49:45.960
you talk about consciousness.

00:49:45.960 --> 00:49:48.530
Think aloud here and explain to us

00:49:48.530 --> 00:49:50.920
how you're thinking about consciousness

00:49:50.920 --> 00:49:54.230
based upon what you've learned
about the brain thus far.

00:49:54.230 --> 00:49:56.870
- Well, unfortunately,
it's a loosely used word,

00:49:56.870 --> 00:49:58.240
and somebody, Stuart Sutherland,

00:49:58.240 --> 00:50:00.110
once said consciousness is a topic

00:50:00.110 --> 00:50:01.490
about which a great deal has been written

00:50:01.490 --> 00:50:02.792
but nothing is known.

00:50:02.792 --> 00:50:03.625
(laughs)

00:50:03.625 --> 00:50:07.093
And I feel sympathetic to his view.

00:50:07.093 --> 00:50:08.550
There are two different questions.

00:50:08.550 --> 00:50:10.300
One is a question of qualia,

00:50:10.300 --> 00:50:11.610
how you can look at something red

00:50:11.610 --> 00:50:13.530
like a red apple, and neurons firing away,

00:50:13.530 --> 00:50:14.880
little wisps of jelly in your brain,

00:50:14.880 --> 00:50:17.040
where's the red sensation come from?

00:50:17.040 --> 00:50:18.490
An ancient question,
still not been solved.

00:50:18.490 --> 00:50:20.160
And then there's the question of self,

00:50:20.160 --> 00:50:22.170
the person who experiences a qualia.

00:50:22.170 --> 00:50:23.283
They're two aspects of the same problem.

00:50:23.283 --> 00:50:26.230
Now if you think of self
as one monolithic entity

00:50:26.230 --> 00:50:27.670
but in fact there's many components to it,

00:50:27.670 --> 00:50:31.170
it's a sense of continuity
in time and space,

00:50:31.170 --> 00:50:35.380
your calendar, your sense
of being anchored in a body,

00:50:35.380 --> 00:50:38.510
your sense of unity,
you, despite a diversity

00:50:38.510 --> 00:50:40.160
of sense impressions and memories,

00:50:40.160 --> 00:50:42.820
you feel like one person
and so on and so forth.

00:50:42.820 --> 00:50:44.600
I think each of these
components can be studied

00:50:44.600 --> 00:50:46.260
by neurologists looking at patients,

00:50:46.260 --> 00:50:47.780
or doing brain imaging.

00:50:47.780 --> 00:50:50.610
And finally some sort of
big picture will emerge,

00:50:50.610 --> 00:50:53.170
but at this stage, we're still studying

00:50:53.170 --> 00:50:55.559
the basic phenomenology,

00:50:55.559 --> 00:50:59.410
phenomena tangentially
related to the problem

00:50:59.410 --> 00:51:01.515
of consciousness, not a head-on collision

00:51:01.515 --> 00:51:02.910
of the problem.

00:51:02.910 --> 00:51:05.468
Your whole question
about what the self is,

00:51:05.468 --> 00:51:07.770
it's called into question

00:51:07.770 --> 00:51:09.820
when you see patients with a disorder

00:51:09.820 --> 00:51:11.950
called anosognosia somatoparaphrenia.

00:51:11.950 --> 00:51:14.120
The patient's right hemisphere stroke,

00:51:14.120 --> 00:51:16.420
ordinarily the left side
completely paralyzed,

00:51:17.893 --> 00:51:18.970
and they agree they're paralyzed,

00:51:18.970 --> 00:51:19.803
they're bothered by it,

00:51:19.803 --> 00:51:20.910
they wanna be treated.

00:51:20.910 --> 00:51:23.010
But a subset of these
patients are paralyzed,

00:51:23.010 --> 00:51:24.752
so here is a patient
with complete paralysis

00:51:24.752 --> 00:51:25.990
of their left arm and left leg,

00:51:25.990 --> 00:51:28.260
an elderly woman, and been paralyzed

00:51:28.260 --> 00:51:31.110
for the last week or so,
right hemisphere stroke.

00:51:31.110 --> 00:51:33.890
Normally, 90% of them,
95% of them will complain

00:51:33.890 --> 00:51:34.993
about their paralysis.

00:51:35.930 --> 00:51:38.672
Now there's about one or 2%

00:51:38.672 --> 00:51:41.360
who are blissfully
indifferent to the paralysis.

00:51:41.360 --> 00:51:43.110
You'll say, "Is there anything
wrong with you, Mrs. D?"

00:51:43.110 --> 00:51:44.837
And they'll say, "No, I'm fine."

00:51:44.837 --> 00:51:46.527
"Can you move your right hand?"

00:51:46.527 --> 00:51:47.997
"Yes, I can move my right hand."

00:51:47.997 --> 00:51:48.867
"What about your left hand?"

00:51:48.867 --> 00:51:50.167
"I can move my left hand."

00:51:51.267 --> 00:51:53.247
"Mrs. D, what is this?"

00:51:54.767 --> 00:51:56.677
"Oh, that's my mother's hand,"

00:51:57.680 --> 00:52:00.607
she would say with a
completely straight face.

00:52:00.607 --> 00:52:03.357
"Your mother's hand?" I say,

00:52:03.357 --> 00:52:04.507
"Where is your mother?"

00:52:07.087 --> 00:52:09.620
"Oh, she's hiding under the table."

00:52:09.620 --> 00:52:10.630
These are intelligent people,

00:52:10.630 --> 00:52:11.760
there's nothing wrong
with their intellect,

00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:13.250
and they're not obviously
emotionally disturbed,

00:52:13.250 --> 00:52:16.480
but she makes up some
completely absurd reason

00:52:16.480 --> 00:52:18.350
for her mother not being visible.

00:52:18.350 --> 00:52:19.490
She's under the table.

00:52:19.490 --> 00:52:20.360
Here comes the best part.

00:52:20.360 --> 00:52:23.597
I say, "Okay, can you touch
my nose with your left hand?"

00:52:24.775 --> 00:52:25.710
Sorry, "With your right hand?"

00:52:25.710 --> 00:52:26.687
Of course she does.

00:52:26.687 --> 00:52:28.460
"Can you touch my nose
with your left hand?"

00:52:28.460 --> 00:52:29.410
She does this.

00:52:34.736 --> 00:52:36.640
Now this implies that somebody in there,

00:52:36.640 --> 00:52:39.320
despite her denial that
the left arm is paralyzed,

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:40.600
knows that the left arm is paralyzed,

00:52:40.600 --> 00:52:43.000
otherwise why would you go and grab it?

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:45.380
Somebody in there also
knows this is her left hand,

00:52:45.380 --> 00:52:46.840
not her mother's,

00:52:46.840 --> 00:52:48.616
otherwise why should she grab it?

00:52:48.616 --> 00:52:50.967
So there are many layers of iterations

00:52:50.967 --> 00:52:53.620
that go into composing
what we call the self,

00:52:53.620 --> 00:52:55.634
and this was brought
home to me very vividly

00:52:55.634 --> 00:52:57.203
in this patient.

00:52:58.240 --> 00:53:02.020
- So in a way you're
learning that the brain

00:53:02.020 --> 00:53:06.300
does not like what you call equilibriums.

00:53:06.300 --> 00:53:08.470
It comes through plasticity

00:53:11.090 --> 00:53:15.680
to a way to configure itself

00:53:15.680 --> 00:53:19.240
so it makes up for the
deficit, is that fair?

00:53:19.240 --> 00:53:21.220
- Well there's some sort
of coherencing mechanism

00:53:21.220 --> 00:53:23.310
undoubtedly, and we don't
quite clearly understand

00:53:23.310 --> 00:53:24.830
what's going on, especially in disorders

00:53:24.830 --> 00:53:27.040
like anosognosia somatoparaphrenia,

00:53:27.040 --> 00:53:29.680
so I have sort not studied it in detail

00:53:29.680 --> 00:53:30.763
for that very reason,

00:53:32.710 --> 00:53:35.590
but the reason I raised is
not because you've studied it,

00:53:35.590 --> 00:53:37.890
or understood it, but to
point out these enigmas

00:53:37.890 --> 00:53:40.600
in neuroscience, surely
relevant to understanding

00:53:40.600 --> 00:53:41.850
the concept of self.

00:53:41.850 --> 00:53:44.070
Some cases, another example
I'd like to give you,

00:53:44.070 --> 00:53:46.890
in which we have solved
the problem, I think,

00:53:46.890 --> 00:53:49.660
is apotemnophilia, unpronounceable name,

00:53:49.660 --> 00:53:52.960
so we changed it to an equally
unpronounceable xenomelia,

00:53:52.960 --> 00:53:54.980
which means, the patient,
or a person I should say,

00:53:54.980 --> 00:53:56.523
they don't regard themselves as patients,

00:53:56.523 --> 00:53:58.290
as a problem,

00:53:58.290 --> 00:54:01.060
all his life has harbored
a deep-seated urge

00:54:01.060 --> 00:54:02.970
to have his left arm removed.

00:54:02.970 --> 00:54:04.680
He's a perfectly normal person,

00:54:04.680 --> 00:54:07.230
led a normal life in society, held a job,

00:54:07.230 --> 00:54:10.833
had a family, had friends,
had a good sense of humor,

00:54:11.890 --> 00:54:15.406
I recently saw a dean
from a medical school

00:54:15.406 --> 00:54:18.800
with the syndrome. He came
to see me at the age of 70.

00:54:18.800 --> 00:54:20.520
It happened five years after retirement.

00:54:20.520 --> 00:54:22.270
And he said he's always had this urge

00:54:22.270 --> 00:54:23.110
to have this arm removed,

00:54:23.110 --> 00:54:24.570
and he wants to understand
what's going on.

00:54:24.570 --> 00:54:26.470
He doesn't want to be cured,

00:54:26.470 --> 00:54:28.680
but he dearly wants to
get his arm removed.

00:54:28.680 --> 00:54:31.420
He doesn't see anything
abnormal about that.

00:54:31.420 --> 00:54:33.747
And this it turns out, it's rare,

00:54:33.747 --> 00:54:35.340
but not quite as rare as people thought.

00:54:35.340 --> 00:54:36.991
You go onto the internet,
you can find people

00:54:36.991 --> 00:54:39.260
with this, quote-unquote, this disorder,

00:54:39.260 --> 00:54:42.250
or this wish to have their arm removed.

00:54:42.250 --> 00:54:44.320
What's going on in their brain?

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:46.520
So I guess you have to
wait for the lecture.

00:54:47.820 --> 00:54:49.120
- Well, one final question.

00:54:49.120 --> 00:54:51.520
You wear so many hats,

00:54:51.520 --> 00:54:56.520
philosopher, medical doctor, neurologist,

00:54:56.630 --> 00:54:58.040
just to name a few.

00:54:58.040 --> 00:55:03.040
How do you separate on
the one hand these roles,

00:55:05.740 --> 00:55:09.360
but on the other hand
learn from each of them

00:55:09.360 --> 00:55:11.390
because you have to be clear

00:55:11.390 --> 00:55:13.590
that when you're a philosopher,
you're speculating.

00:55:13.590 --> 00:55:14.423
- Yeah.

00:55:14.423 --> 00:55:15.256
- It's not science.

00:55:15.256 --> 00:55:17.280
- You sort of have to keep the
compartments quite distinct

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:18.710
in your brain, in your mind.

00:55:18.710 --> 00:55:20.300
When you're seeing a patient as a patient,

00:55:20.300 --> 00:55:22.370
I don't see patients clinically,

00:55:22.370 --> 00:55:27.200
but I do help with the
treatment, devise new treatments,

00:55:27.200 --> 00:55:29.130
and when you see him as a patient,

00:55:29.130 --> 00:55:30.620
it's a very different mindset

00:55:30.620 --> 00:55:33.490
when you're doing experiments on them,

00:55:33.490 --> 00:55:37.580
and that's very important obviously.

00:55:37.580 --> 00:55:39.180
And the philosopher aspect of it

00:55:40.480 --> 00:55:42.230
is yet again is a different matter.

00:55:44.180 --> 00:55:45.360
I haven't thought about it in detail,

00:55:45.360 --> 00:55:48.720
so I'm not sure how easy it
is to answer that question.

00:55:48.720 --> 00:55:51.611
- Well, on that note, I
wanna thank you very much

00:55:51.611 --> 00:55:55.260
for being here and helping us understand

00:55:55.260 --> 00:55:58.250
how you understand the brain

00:55:58.250 --> 00:56:02.010
and this emerging field of
neurology, thank you very much.

00:56:02.010 --> 00:56:03.300
- Thank you very much.

00:56:03.300 --> 00:56:05.456
- And thank you very much for joining us

00:56:05.456 --> 00:56:09.096
for this Conversation with History.

00:56:09.096 --> 00:56:11.679
(upbeat music)

